Comment (src/views/admin/NotificationsView.vue:1431):
`queueJobSearchReload()` schedules a debounced `loadJobs()` call, but the timeout isn’t cleared when the user leaves the Deliveries tab. If someone types in the search box and switches tabs within 300ms, the queued callback will still fire and hit `/api/admin/notifications/jobs` in the background (even though Deliveries is inactive). Consider clearing `jobsSearchDebounceTimer` when `activeTab` changes away from `deliveries`, and/or guarding inside the timeout callback (e.g., only call `loadJobs()` if `activeTab.value === 'deliveries'`).
Implementation guidance: In src/views/admin/NotificationsView.vue, prevent the debounced deliveries search reload from firing after the user leaves the Deliveries tab. Add a small helper such as clearJobsSearchDebounceTimer() near queueJobSearchReload() that checks jobsSearchDebounceTimer, calls window.clearTimeout(jobsSearchDebounceTimer), and sets jobsSearchDebounceTimer = undefined. Use that helper in queueJobSearchReload() before scheduling a new timeout and in onUnmounted() instead of duplicating the clear logic. In the timeout callback, set jobsSearchDebounceTimer = undefined and guard before calling loadJobs(): if activeTab.value !== 'deliveries', return. Also update the activeTab watcher so when tab !== 'deliveries' it clears the pending jobs search debounce timer along with stopping auto-refresh. Do not remove the existing @input="queueJobSearchReload" binding or change loadJobs() pagination behavior; the debounced reload must still call loadJobs() with no cursor when Deliveries remains active.
